solution: ```class Solution {
    public int rearrangeCharacters(String s, String target) {
        int[] sCount = new int[26];
        int[] tCount = new int[26];
        for (char c : s.toCharArray()) sCount[c - 'a']++;
        for (char c : target.toCharArray()) tCount[c - 'a']++;
        int maxCopies = Integer.MAX_VALUE;
        for (int i = 0; i < 26; i++) {
            if (tCount[i] == 0) continue;
            maxCopies = Math.min(maxCopies, sCount[i] / tCount[i]);
        }
        return maxCopies;
    }
}```
efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(n + m)
space complexity: O(1)
energy implications: LOW
explanation: Count frequency of each character in both strings, then the bottleneck is the minimum ratio of counts for every character required by target. This single-pass counting and constant-space array approach is optimal for the given constraints.

